title: Miss Selfridge
description:
Trendy clothes

Miss Selfridge is a major UK high street store which began as the young fashion section of Selfridges department store in London in the 1960s. Miss Selfridge got its name when Charles Clore, creater of Selfridges, saw a window display in the Bonwit Teller store in New York which showed "Miss Bonwit" dresses and skirts aimed specifically at teenagers.

title: Fitzroy Tavern
description:
The Fitzroy Tavern.Built in 1883 as a Coffee House,then The Hundred Marks Pub in 1887,then named the present Fitzroy Tavern,in 1919.During the 1920's to 1940's,it was a Bohemian focal point for artists and intellectuals.
This was a regular haunt for notable folks such as Dylan Thomas,George Orwell,Malcolm Lowry and many other poets,artists,broadcasters and politicians..that is until it was superseded by the  nearby Wheatsheaf pub in Rathbone Place

title: Hard Rock Cafe London
description:
The first HRC in the world!

Eric Clapton and Pete Townsend were the first and second to lend/donate guitars, rest is history.

They say you never forget your first. First love, first kiss, first pint. Well, this battered old Fender Lead II guitar is the very first piece of rock memorabilia acquired in what was to become the greatest collection the world has ever seen. When British blues giant Eric Clapton suggested that his favorite restaurant, the Hard Rock Cafe, reserve his preferred table with a plaque, we suggested his guitar instead. The rest is history. It's fitting that such an important moment was provided by Slowhand himself. From his days with the Yardbirds to the Bluesbreakers (“Clapton is God!”) to Cream and his colossal solo success, Eric has made a career of important moments. We've had bigger, flashier, and louder pieces through the years, but we'll never forget our first. This humble red axe still lives at the Hard Rock London. Right where

title: Le Gavroche
description:
43 Upper Brook Street, London W1K 7QR, United Kingdom
020 7408 0881

http://www.le-gavroche.co.uk/

Le Gavroche is a restaurant at 43 Upper Brook Street in London's Mayfair. It was opened in 1967 by the brilliant brothers Michel and Albert Roux, although the original premises were on Sloane Street.

Michel and Albert have certainly done more to improve the quality of food and cooking in England than anyone else - the top English restaurants are now up there with the very best in the world.

It serves classical French food, although some dishes come with something of a modern twist.

In 1982 it became the first restaurant in the UK to be awarded three Michelin stars.

Albert's son, Michel Roux Jr took over the kitchen in 1991 and remains the current head chef as of 2006. Under his stewardship, Le Gavroche has retained two Michelin stars and has been consistently placed in Restaurant's Top 50.

Michel left to run the Waterside Inn in Bray, Berkshire from 1973, which still has three Michelin stars - his son Alain now is head chef.

Alumni in kitchen include Marco Pierre White, the first English cook to gain 3 Michelin stars, since relinquished when MPW retired, and Gordon Ramsey who now has 3 stars too at his Chelsea restaurant.  So le Gavroche not only had three stars but has two chefs who have each gone on to have three stars too.
